{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "CarbonCycle",
        "description": "Seven-reservoir model of the global carbon cycle from Schmitz (2002), as presented in Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Ch. 22 (Global Cycles: Sulfur and Carbon), Table 22.1 and Fig. 22.6, pp. 1009-1015. Carbon is tracked as a mass (kg) in seven reservoirs — atmosphere (M1), warm ocean surface waters (M2), cool ocean surface waters (M3), deep ocean waters (M4), terrestrial biota (M5), soils and detritus (M6), and fossil fuel reserves (M7) — plus a dimensionless land-use-change scaling factor G that modulates biotic uptake (Eq. 22.21). Inter-reservoir transport uses first-order exchange coefficients k_ij (Table 22.1), except three nonlinear fluxes carried as auxiliary algebraic variables: the saturating atmosphere-to-biota photosynthetic uptake F15 (Eq. 22.19) and the carbonate-buffer power-law ocean-to-atmosphere outgassing fluxes F21 and F31 (Eq. 22.18). Three external forcing parameters drive the anthropogenic perturbation — fossil fuel emissions Ff, deforestation Fd, and reforestation Fr — all zero by default, recovering the preindustrial (~1850) steady state. The system is an 11-unknown ODE model (8 time-differentiated reservoir states M1-M7,G + 3 algebraic flux states F15/F21/F31) with 11 equations and 25 parameters (22 first-order/derived constants + 3 forcing fluxes). All quantities are SI (kg for mass, s for time); the source material's Pg C (1 Pg = 1e12 kg) and years (1 yr = 31557600 s) are converted to maintain unit consistency. Migrated from AtmosphericDynamics.jl@816cc391 src/global_cycles.jl:115 (`CarbonCycle` @component).",
        "tags": [
            "atmospheric_dynamics",
            "global-cycles",
            "carbon-cycle",
            "biogeochemistry",
            "ode-system",
            "seinfeld-pandis",
            "schmitz-2002"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-17T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "AtmosphericDynamics.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-x6ds)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., & Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd ed. Wiley. Chapter 22 (Global Cycles: Sulfur and Carbon), Table 22.1 and Figure 22.6, pp. 1009-1015 — the seven-reservoir global carbon cycle, first-order exchange coefficients, nonlinear ocean outgassing (Eq. 22.18), photosynthetic uptake (Eq. 22.19), and the land-use-change scaling factor (Eq. 22.21)."
            },
            {
                "citation": "Schmitz, R. A. (2002). The Earth's carbon cycle: A chemical engineering perspective. Chemical Engineering Education, 36(4), 296-309 — original formulation of the seven-box global carbon cycle model with preindustrial steady-state reservoir masses and exchange coefficients."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "CarbonCycle": {
            "reference": {
                "citation": "Seinfeld & Pandis (2006), Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics, 2nd ed., Ch. 22, Table 22.1 / Fig. 22.6, pp. 1009-1015; after Schmitz, R. A. (2002), Chem. Eng. Educ. 36(4), 296.",
                "notes": "source_ref: AtmosphericDynamics.jl@816cc3918e1eef2c2ee6d8fa8dd73c8f13a85a47:src/global_cycles.jl:115\n\nUpstream `CarbonCycle` is an MTK `@component` returning `System(eqs, t; name)` with 3 `@parameters` (Ff, Fd, Fr — external anthropogenic forcing fluxes, kg/s), 22 `@constants` (10 first-order inter-reservoir exchange coefficients k_ij; 2 carbonate-buffer exponents β2/β3; the biotic uptake threshold/saturation pair γ_c/Γ_c; the land-use fractions a_d/a_r; the derived photosynthetic-uptake rate k15; the preindustrial ocean reference fluxes F21_pre/F31_pre; and the preindustrial normalization masses M2_pre/M3_pre/M5_0), 11 `@variables` (the 7 reservoir masses M1-M7, the land-use scaling factor G, and the 3 auxiliary flux variables F15_flux/F21_flux/F31_flux), and 11 equations — 8 first-order ODEs D(M1..M7), D(G) and 3 algebraic flux definitions. It implements Schmitz (2002) as presented in Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Ch. 22 Table 22.1 / Eqs. 22.18-22.21.\n\nVariable-classification convention: MTK reports `length(unknowns(CarbonCycle())) == 11`, `length(parameters(CarbonCycle())) == 25`, `length(equations(CarbonCycle())) == 11` (upstream test `CarbonCycle - Structural`, test/global_cycles_test.jl:107-116). The .esm preserves this exactly. All 11 `@variables` are encoded as `type: state`: M1-M7 and G are genuine time-differentiated ODE states and carry the upstream initializer as `default` (the preindustrial initial condition); F15_flux, F21_flux, F31_flux are algebraic states — each is the LHS of one non-differential equation — and carry no `default` (they are determined by the algebraic equations, not initial-valued). After `mtkcompile` the three flux states move to the system's `observed` set; the canonical Python runner resolves them through its topological algebraic-state substitution loop. The 22 MTK `@constants` appear in `ModelingToolkit.parameters(sys)` alongside the 3 `@parameters`, so all 25 are encoded as `type: parameter`; only Ff/Fd/Fr are intended to be varied (the constants reproduce Table 22.1 and should be treated as fixed).\n\nUnit conversion (SI throughout): the source material (Schmitz 2002 / S&P Table 22.1) is stated in Pg C and per-year rates. The upstream @component converts every quantity to SI at construction — masses to kg (1 Pg = 1e12 kg) and rates to s^-1 / kg s^-1 (1 yr = 31557600 s, the Julian year). The .esm `default` values are the post-conversion SI numbers: e.g. k12 = 0.0931 yr^-1 / 31557600 = 2.950160975486095e-9 s^-1; k15 = 147.27e12 kg / 31557600 s = 4666704.692372044 kg/s; M1(0) = 612 Pg C = 6.12e14 kg. k15 is itself a derived constant: at the preindustrial steady state F15 = 100 Pg C/yr, M1 = 612 Pg, γ = 62 Pg, Γ = 198 Pg, so k15 = 100·(M1+Γ)/(M1-γ) = 100·810/550 ≈ 147.27 Pg C/yr (Eq. 22.19 inverted).\n\nEquation set (matches src/global_cycles.jl:213-251 verbatim, re-grouped as positive-minus-negative sums so every term carries an explicit sign without a unary-minus node):\n  F15_flux = k15·G·max(0, (M1-γ_c)/(M1+Γ_c))         — Eq. 22.19, saturating photosynthetic uptake; the max(0,·) floor zeroes uptake when atmospheric carbon drops below the threshold γ_c.\n  F21_flux = F21_pre·(M2/M2_pre)^β2                   — Eq. 22.18, nonlinear (carbonate-buffer) warm-ocean outgassing.\n  F31_flux = F31_pre·(M3/M3_pre)^β3                   — Eq. 22.18, nonlinear cool-ocean outgassing.\n  D(M1) = F21+F31+k51·M5+k61·M6+Ff+Fd − ((k12+k13)·M1+F15+Fr)   — Table 22.1 Eq. 1, atmosphere.\n  D(M2) = k12·M1+k42·M4 − ((k23+k24)·M2+F21)                    — Table 22.1 Eq. 2, warm ocean.\n  D(M3) = k13·M1+k23·M2+k43·M4 − (k34·M3+F31)                   — Table 22.1 Eq. 3, cool ocean.\n  D(M4) = k24·M2+k34·M3 − (k42+k43)·M4                          — Table 22.1 Eq. 4, deep ocean.\n  D(M5) = F15+Fr − ((k51+k56)·M5+Fd)                            — Table 22.1 Eq. 5, terrestrial biota.\n  D(M6) = k56·M5 − k61·M6                                       — Table 22.1 Eq. 6, soils/detritus.\n  D(M7) = −Ff                                                   — Table 22.1 Eq. 7, fossil fuel reserves.\n  D(G)  = (a_r·Fr − a_d·Fd)/M5_0                                — Eq. 22.21, land-use-change scaling factor (the upstream −(a_d·Fd−a_r·Fr)/M5_0 distributed).\n\nThe `max` operator at equations[0].rhs is a first-class ESM expression op (esm-schema.json ExpressionNode op enum; AGENTS.md §1 lists max among the single-sourced ops) and round-trips through every canonical runner — 21 committed .esm files use it. The `mtk2esm` scaffolder emits a spurious gt-p3ep gap warning for `max`; this is a known false positive (gt-p3ep tracks @register_symbolic lookup tables, not arithmetic ops) and the migration tracker classifies this component `blocking_gap: none`, so this .esm carries no schema-gap marker.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-6): all numeric assertions are pinned from a reference simulation of the upstream `CarbonCycle()` MTK system (Tsit5, reltol=1e-10, abstol=1e-12) — the genuine source model, not a re-export of this file. rel=1e-6 absorbs the integrator-choice difference between the Julia walker (Tsit5) and the Python gate-of-record (scipy LSODA, rtol=1e-10, atol=1e-14) over the long carbon-cycle integrations (10-100 model years = 3.2e8-3.2e9 s); it is the spec §6.6.4 default and matches the sibling ODE-migration convention (methane_ode.esm). The reservoir masses span 1.4e14-3.7e16 kg and the fluxes 5e5-3.5e6 kg/s, all far above any abstol floor, so rel alone gates every assertion.\n\nUpstream test reproduction (test/global_cycles_test.jl):\n- `CarbonCycle - Structural` (lines 107-116) — reproduced by the structural shape: 11 `type: state` variables, 25 `type: parameter` variables, 11 entries in `equations`.\n- `CarbonCycle - Preindustrial Steady State` (lines 118-149, Ff=Fd=Fr=0, 10 yr, every reservoir within rtol=0.01 of its initial value) — reproduced and tightened by tests `preindustrial_initial_state` and `preindustrial_steady_state`, which pin M1-M7,G,F15/F21/F31 at t=0, 5 yr, 10 yr.\n- `CarbonCycle - Response to Fossil Fuel Emissions` (lines 151-185, Ff=5 Pg C/yr, 100 yr, M1 increases, M7 decreases, M7 depletes by exactly 500 Pg C, total carbon conserved to rtol=1e-6) — reproduced by `fossil_fuel_emissions_5pg`; the pinned M7 = 4.8e15 kg confirms the 500 Pg C (5.0e14 kg) drawdown, and summing the pinned M1-M7 at t=0 vs t=100 yr confirms conservation.\n- `CarbonCycle - Qualitative Response` (lines 187-212, Ff=3 Pg C/yr, 50 yr, M1 increases, warm/cool ocean both absorb CO2) — reproduced by `fossil_fuel_emissions_3pg`; the pinned M2 > 7.30e14 and M3 > 1.40e14 confirm ocean uptake.\nTests `deforestation_response` and `reforestation_response` extend coverage to the Fd and Fr forcing channels and the land-use scaling factor G: at Fd=Fr=2 Pg C/yr over 50 yr, G reaches 1 − 0.23·100/580 = 0.96034 (deforestation) and 1 + 1.0·100/580 = 1.17241 (reforestation), the closed-form integral of the constant-forcing D(G) equation.\n\nUnit balance (verified): every equation balances dimensionally. The k_ij·M terms are s^-1·kg = kg/s; F15/F21/F31, Ff, Fd, Fr are kg/s; so all D(M) ODEs are kg/s ✓. D(G) is (1·kg/s)/kg = s^-1 with G dimensionless ✓. In F15, (M1-γ_c)/(M1+Γ_c) is kg/kg = dimensionless and k15·G is kg/s ✓. In F21/F31, (M/M_pre)^β is dimensionless and F_pre is kg/s ✓. SI (kg, s) throughout; no unit conversion at parse or runtime."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1.0e-6
            },
            "variables": {
                "M1": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "kg",
                    "default": 612000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Carbon mass in the atmosphere [kg] — reservoir 1 of the Schmitz (2002) seven-box model. Preindustrial initial condition 612 Pg C = 6.12e14 kg (Seinfeld & Pandis Table 22.1). Driven by ocean outgassing, biotic and soil respiration, and anthropogenic forcing; drawn down by ocean uptake and photosynthesis."
                },
                "M2": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "kg",
                    "default": 730000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Carbon mass in warm ocean surface waters [kg] — reservoir 2. Preindustrial initial condition 730 Pg C = 7.30e14 kg (Table 22.1)."
                },
                "M3": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "kg",
                    "default": 140000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Carbon mass in cool ocean surface waters [kg] — reservoir 3. Preindustrial initial condition 140 Pg C = 1.40e14 kg (Table 22.1)."
                },
                "M4": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "kg",
                    "default": 37000000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Carbon mass in deep ocean waters [kg] — reservoir 4, the dominant carbon store. Preindustrial initial condition 37000 Pg C = 3.70e16 kg (Table 22.1)."
                },
                "M5": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "kg",
                    "default": 580000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Carbon mass in terrestrial biota [kg] — reservoir 5. Preindustrial initial condition 580 Pg C = 5.80e14 kg (Table 22.1)."
                },
                "M6": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "kg",
                    "default": 1500000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Carbon mass in soils and detritus [kg] — reservoir 6. Preindustrial initial condition 1500 Pg C = 1.50e15 kg (Table 22.1)."
                },
                "M7": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "kg",
                    "default": 5300000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Carbon mass remaining in fossil fuel reserves [kg] — reservoir 7. Preindustrial initial condition 5300 Pg C = 5.30e15 kg (Table 22.1). Depleted at rate Ff by fossil fuel combustion (D(M7) = −Ff)."
                },
                "G": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 1.0,
                    "description": "Land-use-change scaling factor for biotic uptake [dimensionless] — Eq. 22.21. Starts at 1 (preindustrial). Permanent deforestation lowers it, reforestation raises it, multiplicatively scaling the photosynthetic uptake flux F15."
                },
                "F15_flux": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "kg/s",
                    "description": "Atmosphere → biota photosynthetic uptake flux [kg/s] — Eq. 22.19. A saturating function of atmospheric carbon M1, scaled by the land-use factor G; the max(0,·) floor zeroes uptake if M1 drops below the threshold γ_c. Algebraic variable (no initial condition); ≈ 100 Pg C/yr at the preindustrial state."
                },
                "F21_flux": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "kg/s",
                    "description": "Warm ocean → atmosphere CO2 outgassing flux [kg/s] — Eq. 22.18. A nonlinear carbonate-buffer power law in warm ocean carbon M2 with exponent β2. Algebraic variable (no initial condition); = F21_pre at the preindustrial state (M2 = M2_pre)."
                },
                "F31_flux": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "kg/s",
                    "description": "Cool ocean → atmosphere CO2 outgassing flux [kg/s] — Eq. 22.18. A nonlinear carbonate-buffer power law in cool ocean carbon M3 with exponent β3. Algebraic variable (no initial condition); = F31_pre at the preindustrial state (M3 = M3_pre)."
                },
                "k12": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "default": 2.950160975486095e-09,
                    "description": "Atmosphere → warm ocean first-order transfer coefficient [s^-1] — Table 22.1: 0.0931 yr^-1 converted to SI (÷ 31557600 s/yr)."
                },
                "k13": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "default": 9.854995310163003e-10,
                    "description": "Atmosphere → cool ocean first-order transfer coefficient [s^-1] — Table 22.1: 0.0311 yr^-1 converted to SI."
                },
                "k23": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "default": 2.474839658275661e-09,
                    "description": "Warm ocean → cool ocean first-order transfer coefficient [s^-1] — Table 22.1: 0.0781 yr^-1 converted to SI."
                },
                "k24": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "default": 5.196846401500749e-10,
                    "description": "Warm ocean → deep ocean first-order transfer coefficient [s^-1] — Table 22.1: 0.0164 yr^-1 converted to SI."
                },
                "k34": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "default": 2.262529469921667e-08,
                    "description": "Cool ocean → deep ocean first-order transfer coefficient [s^-1] — Table 22.1: 0.714 yr^-1 converted to SI."
                },
                "k42": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "default": 5.989048596851471e-11,
                    "description": "Deep ocean → warm ocean first-order transfer coefficient [s^-1] — Table 22.1: 0.00189 yr^-1 converted to SI."
                },
                "k43": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "default": 3.6124420107993004e-11,
                    "description": "Deep ocean → cool ocean first-order transfer coefficient [s^-1] — Table 22.1: 0.00114 yr^-1 converted to SI."
                },
                "k51": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "default": 2.7315131695692954e-09,
                    "description": "Terrestrial biota → atmosphere first-order transfer coefficient [s^-1] — Table 22.1: 0.0862 yr^-1 converted to SI (biotic respiration)."
                },
                "k56": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "default": 2.7315131695692954e-09,
                    "description": "Terrestrial biota → soils/detritus first-order transfer coefficient [s^-1] — Table 22.1: 0.0862 yr^-1 converted to SI (litterfall)."
                },
                "k61": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "default": 1.055213324207164e-09,
                    "description": "Soils/detritus → atmosphere first-order transfer coefficient [s^-1] — Table 22.1: 0.0333 yr^-1 converted to SI (soil respiration)."
                },
                "β2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 9.4,
                    "description": "Warm ocean carbonate-buffer exponent [dimensionless] — Table 22.1 = 9.4. Sets the nonlinearity of warm-ocean CO2 outgassing: F21 ∝ (M2/M2_pre)^β2."
                },
                "β3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 10.2,
                    "description": "Cool ocean carbonate-buffer exponent [dimensionless] — Table 22.1 = 10.2. Sets the nonlinearity of cool-ocean CO2 outgassing: F31 ∝ (M3/M3_pre)^β3."
                },
                "γ_c": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg",
                    "default": 62000000000000.0,
                    "description": "CO2 uptake threshold for biota [kg] — Table 22.1 = 62 Pg C = 6.2e13 kg. Atmospheric carbon below this value yields zero photosynthetic uptake (the max(0,·) floor in Eq. 22.19)."
                },
                "Γ_c": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg",
                    "default": 198000000000000.0,
                    "description": "CO2 saturation parameter for biota [kg] — Table 22.1 = 198 Pg C = 1.98e14 kg. Sets the half-saturation scale of the photosynthetic uptake response (Eq. 22.19 denominator)."
                },
                "a_d": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.23,
                    "description": "Fraction of deforested area permanently unavailable for regrowth [dimensionless] — Table 22.1 = 0.23. Drives the land-use scaling factor G downward under deforestation (Eq. 22.21)."
                },
                "a_r": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 1.0,
                    "description": "Fraction of reforested area that increases biota [dimensionless] — Table 22.1 = 1.0. Drives the land-use scaling factor G upward under reforestation (Eq. 22.21)."
                },
                "k15": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/s",
                    "default": 4666704.692372044,
                    "description": "Atmosphere → biota base photosynthetic uptake rate [kg/s] — derived constant. Calibrated so the preindustrial F15 = 100 Pg C/yr: k15 = 100·(M1+Γ)/(M1−γ) = 100·810/550 ≈ 147.27 Pg C/yr, converted to SI (147.27e12 / 31557600)."
                },
                "F21_pre": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/s",
                    "default": 1837909.093213679,
                    "description": "Preindustrial warm ocean → atmosphere reference flux [kg/s] — Table 22.1: 58 Pg C/yr converted to SI. Prefactor of the F21 carbonate-buffer power law."
                },
                "F31_pre": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/s",
                    "default": 570385.5806525211,
                    "description": "Preindustrial cool ocean → atmosphere reference flux [kg/s] — Table 22.1: 18 Pg C/yr converted to SI. Prefactor of the F31 carbonate-buffer power law."
                },
                "M2_pre": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg",
                    "default": 730000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Preindustrial warm ocean surface carbon [kg] — 730 Pg C = 7.30e14 kg. Normalization mass for the F21 power law (M2/M2_pre)^β2."
                },
                "M3_pre": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg",
                    "default": 140000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Preindustrial cool ocean surface carbon [kg] — 140 Pg C = 1.40e14 kg. Normalization mass for the F31 power law (M3/M3_pre)^β3."
                },
                "M5_0": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg",
                    "default": 580000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Preindustrial terrestrial biota carbon [kg] — 580 Pg C = 5.80e14 kg. Normalization mass in the land-use-change equation for G (Eq. 22.21)."
                },
                "Ff": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/s",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Fossil fuel combustion emission flux [kg/s] — external forcing, default 0 (preindustrial). Adds carbon to the atmosphere M1 and depletes the fossil reservoir M7. A value of 5 Pg C/yr corresponds to 5.0e12/31557600 ≈ 1.5844e5 kg/s."
                },
                "Fd": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/s",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Deforestation carbon flux [kg/s] — external forcing, default 0. Transfers carbon from terrestrial biota M5 to the atmosphere M1 and lowers the land-use scaling factor G."
                },
                "Fr": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/s",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Reforestation carbon flux [kg/s] — external forcing, default 0. Transfers carbon from the atmosphere M1 to terrestrial biota M5 and raises the land-use scaling factor G."
                }
            },
            "equations": [
                {
                    "_comment": "Eq. 22.19 — atmosphere-to-biota photosynthetic uptake (saturating, land-use-scaled). The max(0, .) floor zeroes uptake when M1 < γ_c.",
                    "lhs": "F15_flux",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            "k15",
                            "G",
                            {
                                "op": "max",
                                "args": [
                                    0.0,
                                    {
                                        "op": "/",
                                        "args": [
                                            {"op": "-", "args": ["M1", "γ_c"]},
                                            {"op": "+", "args": ["M1", "Γ_c"]}
                                        ]
                                    }
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "_comment": "Eq. 22.18 — nonlinear warm-ocean-to-atmosphere CO2 outgassing (carbonate buffer).",
                    "lhs": "F21_flux",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            "F21_pre",
                            {
                                "op": "^",
                                "args": [
                                    {"op": "/", "args": ["M2", "M2_pre"]},
                                    "β2"
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "_comment": "Eq. 22.18 — nonlinear cool-ocean-to-atmosphere CO2 outgassing (carbonate buffer).",
                    "lhs": "F31_flux",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            "F31_pre",
                            {
                                "op": "^",
                                "args": [
                                    {"op": "/", "args": ["M3", "M3_pre"]},
                                    "β3"
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "_comment": "Table 22.1 Eq. 1 — atmosphere carbon balance.",
                    "lhs": {"op": "D", "wrt": "t", "args": ["M1"]},
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "-",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "+",
                                "args": [
                                    "F21_flux",
                                    "F31_flux",
                                    {"op": "*", "args": ["k51", "M5"]},
                                    {"op": "*", "args": ["k61", "M6"]},
                                    "Ff",
                                    "Fd"
                                ]
                            },
                            {
                                "op": "+",
                                "args": [
                                    {"op": "*", "args": [{"op": "+", "args": ["k12", "k13"]}, "M1"]},
                                    "F15_flux",
                                    "Fr"
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "_comment": "Table 22.1 Eq. 2 — warm ocean surface carbon balance.",
                    "lhs": {"op": "D", "wrt": "t", "args": ["M2"]},
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "-",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "+",
                                "args": [
                                    {"op": "*", "args": ["k12", "M1"]},
                                    {"op": "*", "args": ["k42", "M4"]}
                                ]
                            },
                            {
                                "op": "+",
                                "args": [
                                    {"op": "*", "args": [{"op": "+", "args": ["k23", "k24"]}, "M2"]},
                                    "F21_flux"
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "_comment": "Table 22.1 Eq. 3 — cool ocean surface carbon balance.",
                    "lhs": {"op": "D", "wrt": "t", "args": ["M3"]},
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "-",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "+",
                                "args": [
                                    {"op": "*", "args": ["k13", "M1"]},
                                    {"op": "*", "args": ["k23", "M2"]},
                                    {"op": "*", "args": ["k43", "M4"]}
                                ]
                            },
                            {
                                "op": "+",
                                "args": [
                                    {"op": "*", "args": ["k34", "M3"]},
                                    "F31_flux"
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "_comment": "Table 22.1 Eq. 4 — deep ocean carbon balance.",
                    "lhs": {"op": "D", "wrt": "t", "args": ["M4"]},
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "-",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "+",
                                "args": [
                                    {"op": "*", "args": ["k24", "M2"]},
                                    {"op": "*", "args": ["k34", "M3"]}
                                ]
                            },
                            {"op": "*", "args": [{"op": "+", "args": ["k42", "k43"]}, "M4"]}
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "_comment": "Table 22.1 Eq. 5 — terrestrial biota carbon balance.",
                    "lhs": {"op": "D", "wrt": "t", "args": ["M5"]},
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "-",
                        "args": [
                            {"op": "+", "args": ["F15_flux", "Fr"]},
                            {
                                "op": "+",
                                "args": [
                                    {"op": "*", "args": [{"op": "+", "args": ["k51", "k56"]}, "M5"]},
                                    "Fd"
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "_comment": "Table 22.1 Eq. 6 — soils and detritus carbon balance.",
                    "lhs": {"op": "D", "wrt": "t", "args": ["M6"]},
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "-",
                        "args": [
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["k56", "M5"]},
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["k61", "M6"]}
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "_comment": "Table 22.1 Eq. 7 — fossil fuel reserve depletion.",
                    "lhs": {"op": "D", "wrt": "t", "args": ["M7"]},
                    "rhs": {"op": "*", "args": [-1.0, "Ff"]}
                },
                {
                    "_comment": "Eq. 22.21 — land-use-change scaling factor for biotic uptake.",
                    "lhs": {"op": "D", "wrt": "t", "args": ["G"]},
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "-",
                                "args": [
                                    {"op": "*", "args": ["a_r", "Fr"]},
                                    {"op": "*", "args": ["a_d", "Fd"]}
                                ]
                            },
                            "M5_0"
                        ]
                    }
                }
